<br>
First and foremost, it was easy...<br>
<br>
But this does not go without saying, that it is easy for many other classes, including but not limited to the pet classes.<br>
<br>
I did have a working knowledge of what mobs had the major hitpoints and which ones did not, as such I did not go to kunark until I was forced for decent EXP at the 30th level in the Overthere.<br>
<br>
I soloed much of my time, and much of it was without worry, but this was all in the Old World, where AC, HP, and Strength of mobs is lower compared to that of every other expansion continent.<br>
<br>
I had no problem getting groups when I needed to up and through my late 30s. However, as I came to the Dreadlands, it got increasingly more difficult, the further I went into my 40s, especially 48 and 49.<br>
<br>
50 is a difficult level, as you're too high for some spots, and not quite high enough for others...I duoed through 50 with another magician in the Dreadlands, and all has gone well since.<br>
<br>
I'm drawing very close to 54 by the end of this week. I have finally come into the recruitment of a very nice, very respectable guild on my server, and I hope dearly that I have put the right impression on them.<br>
<br>
<br>
However, in regards to balance...<br>
<br>
I believe a near-perfect equilibrium has been met at these lower levels if you comare myself, and any other class of a similar level and similar equipment.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, as I got into my twenties and stumbled upon this place by some chance (My memory slips as to how I got here)...I became more aware of the problems, and began to notice that quite a few of the melee types were benefitting heavily from gear, where I stayed relatively the same, punctuated equilibrium.<br>
<br>
As I escalated in levels, the rift between the 2 types in everquest grew larger, melees were accelerating rapidly, but likewise, I felt I stayed competitive.<br>
<br>
The 51+ game is where it does change, and refinement needs to be done...A fine balance does need to be sought for casters between gear and spell dependance.<br>
<br>
While the caster background of relying on powerful spells, many purchased, cannot be ignored. We find ourselves in an awkward position.<br>
<br>
A) If beneficial spells were dropped, in much the same manner as melee weapons...All with varying degrees of power, the rift my begin to close.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Example:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> There is the purchased line of spells that we are all used to, however there is a PLETHORA of other spells that drop, with the same effects, but in varying degrees of casting speed and damage done (as well as other effects of course, such as amount of damage on a DS, and duration of that DS)...In much a similar fashion to the 1 hand slashing skill for melees. One hand slash is a universal skill, however hundreds of weapons are applied to it, and so on and so forth.<br>
<br>
B) Focus items are unavoidable, but they should be droppable, and some NOT droppable...In a much similar fashion to melees.<br>
<br>
HOWEVER, the problem with the above suggestions is this...<br>
<br>
Melees weaponry drops like hotcakes, even very good ones, highly sought after weaponry...The highly sought after spells...Do not.<br>
<br>
This is where I believe the issue lies, there is only one denomination of a certain type of spell (such as, there is only one type of 54 water pet)...There is no varying degree of differentiation.<br>
<br>
Likewise, these highly sought after spells and focus items, would most likely be sold for insane prices...For instance, Kodiak's Endless Intellect, is being sold for 60k on Bertoxxulous, but I have counted 40 copies in 30 days of the spell, hardly rare...But melees (and this is the gospel truth, the price on this spell was first set by a melee on our server, and the majority of the sellers OF this spell are melees) continue to overestimate the value of spells, because as I said, there is only 1 type.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Recap:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
1. Focus items need to be (and are) being implemented as quested, no drop, and not no drop.<br>
<br>
2. Perhaps variations of identical spells need to be produce, varying in effectiveness and power (Much like a 1 hand slash weapon)<br>
<br>
3. Drop rates need to be increased yet again on rare spells, as they are frequently the most power...Verant seems hell-bent on keeping a bottleneck on powerful spells, only putting casters further behind melees who have a plethora of very good weaponry (melee spells), that drop regularly, or can be purchased.<br>
<br>
<br>
4. The major issue is the relative ease of acquiring a good weapon for melees, and the relative difficulty of acquiring a good spell for casters.<br>
<br>
<br>
I know I've touched on several issues within this thread, and not all of them are quite on topic. But that's my analysis of the pre and post-51 game.<br>
